[11:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the settings really quickly. So for the first node here is where you would select either the FP8 version or the full BF16 OV model. If you have 16 or 24 GB of VRAM, then you can only use the'

[11:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'FP8 version. If you have over 32 GB of VRAM, then you can try the full BF-16 model. Here, you should set this CPU offload model to true so that it will first load the models onto your VRAM,'

[11:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and for any excess memory, it will try to load this onto your computer\'s RAM. If you don\'t select this and you have low VRAM, then you\'re probably going to get an out of memory error. And then for the device, you should set this to the'

[11:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'device number of your GPU, which in most cases is just zero. For those of you with multiple GPUs, then you can specify the number of your device over here. And then in this node, we will load the one'

[12:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2.2 VA file. So make sure you click on the dropown and select 1 2.2 VA. And then same with this text encoder. Again, if you have low VRAM, then you would use the FP8 version. If you have over 32 GB'

[12:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of VRAM, then you can try this BF-16 version. And then afterwards here, you can select from different accelerator methods such as flash attention or Sage Attention. It should automatically'

[12:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'detect what you have. So if you\'re not sure, just leave this at auto. Now, moving down here, here is where you would enter the prompt describing the video as well as the dialogue and the voice and audio that you want. If you\'re'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doing text to video, you can just describe the video with a normal prompt. But then if you want to get any character to say something, you would have to enclose the dialogue with this start and end tag like this. And then'

[12:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can also specify, you know, the voice that you want as well as the background audio within these oddcap tags. In fact, if you refer to the original OV GitHub repo, they give you a'

[13:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ton of text to video as well as imagetovideo prompt examples so you can get a sense of how to format your prompt effectively. Anyways, going back to here, here is where you would specify'

[13:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the height and width of your final video. Here\'s the seed. So, for beginners, the seed is basically the starting configuration of random noise of your generation. All you need to know is that if you keep all the settings the'

[13:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same and use the same prompt and the same seed, you\'re going to get the exact same generation as before. If you change the seed but keep all the settings the same, then you\'re going to get a slightly different generation. So, I tend to just set the seed to randomize'

[13:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so that I\'ll get a different generation even if I use the same prompt. And then for the solver name, this is basically the algorithm used to generate the video. I\'m just going to leave it at the defaults. For sampling steps, this is'

[13:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how many steps the model takes before outputting your final video. So, in general, the more steps you have, the higher quality your generation will be, but it\'s going to take slower and you\'re going to get diminishing returns if you'

[14:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'set it to too many steps. Conversely, if you set it to fewer steps, it\'s going to generate faster, but at the sacrifice of some quality. And then notice that down here, you can also specify some negative prompts for the video and the audio. And'

[14:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these are basically elements that you want to exclude from the video or audio. Anyways, this workflow includes some helpful notes for each node. So you can refer to these for more guidance. And'

[14:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then over here is where you would upload an image if you want to do image to video. In other words, if you want to use an image as a reference frame. So for example, I can upload an image and then if I want to use image to video, I'

[14:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would simply connect this node to over here. And that\'s pretty much it. And then going over here, here is where you would specify the frame rate, which is just 24 frames per second by default.'

[14:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
